 Joshua Jacobs, on July 26, 2013 at 8:38 am said:		

When I think about MVP’s I can’t help but see examples of cases where the opposite was successful: the iPhone, the Kindle. These were massive projects with huge backend engineering and operations, with huge big-bang launches.
Is there a rubric for determining when a project can benefit from an MVP vs when a Big Bang release is more appropriate?
Is it possible that some projects will only be successful on scale, and that aiming for an MVP is sometimes a *bad idea*?
LikeLike

Reply 





 john haro (@johnharo), on July 26, 2013 at 9:53 am said:		

Great point, however
1) Apple and Amazon have considerable resources… they can afford to stumble, and they can afford to take MANY years (iPhone took many many years) to develop and quietly test the product and business models.
2) There are countless counterexamples to iPhones’s/Kindle ereader success… Google is not afraid to fail publicly and does so often enough (Google TV, Google Wave, etc).  They also make nearly all of their money selling advertising so they will survive to try the next big thing (balloon based internet services for the 3rd world for instance)
Those companies can fail and probably not sink.  Most startups may not survive a large investment in engineering that produces no customers.
LikeLike

Reply 





 Joshua Jacobs, on July 26, 2013 at 11:07 am said:		

Thanks for your replies @john and @Lilia. 
At the risk of venturing further into hypotheticals…
Could Google have failed smaller in those cases where it does fail?
Could Apple, Amazon, … have been more successful with a lean/MVP strategy? 
Do opportunities that aren’t a good fit for MVP approaches demand bigger budgets and higher failure tolerance?
LikeLike

Reply 





 Lilia Tovbin, on July 26, 2013 at 1:12 pm said:		

If you are Apple/Amazon/Google you have enough data to base your business decisions on and enough resources to build a viable product, so you don’t really need an MVP. They also have their brand to protect so have to be more sensitive to quality of the products they introduce.
“Do opportunities that aren’t a good fit for MVP approaches demand bigger budgets …?”
Not necessarily. In the case of reinventing an existing product or idea your cost to market is actually lower – innovation is expensive, imitation is cheap and effective. MVP is a method for learning (validating) who your customers are and what they want and willing to pay for while keeping the cost to a minimum.
LikeLike

Reply 











 Lilia Tovbin, on July 26, 2013 at 9:29 am said:		

I can think of 2 factors that determine a need for an MVP:
1. Whether the product idea is new or just a variation/improvement/extension of an already validated product. Many founders say “I can do this better and cheaper than company X” and improve upon an existing product that already has a proven market.
2. Whether business survival or even existence depends on the success of the product or not. In cases of startups, not validating a product is intolerable risk compared to launching of another product for a big established company.
LikeLike

Reply 





 Lee De La Houssaye, on July 29, 2013 at 10:20 am said:		

This is all about defining the product. Is the product the technology or the output? What the product IS depends on the problem that the team is trying to solve. If the problem is that there is no way to get high resolution data, the plane / helicopter idea is a good one, but if the plane / helicopter thing is already being done, as one commenter pointed out, then the value proposition may be that doing it with drones is cheaper or somehow better than using manned aircraft, in which case they will have to develop a prototype to prove that out.
